Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stourton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of three places named Stourton (Staffs, Wilts, Warwicks).","2  English:  see  Sturton  .","3  English: locative name, perhaps occasionally from Storrington (Sussex), which is recorded as  <i>Storgetune</i> in 1086."],"variants":[{"name":"Storton","meanings":["English:  see  Stourton  ."]},{"name":"Sturton","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Sturton le Steeple (Notts), Great Sturton (Lincs), Sturton by Stow (Lincs), or possibly Sturton (Northumb), all of which place-names share the same etymology and early spellings as   Stratton  .","2  English:  see  Stourton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Stourton was born in 1245, in Stourton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Alexander de Stourton 2 Children. He married Parnell of Warwickshire in 1282, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1298, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1245–1298":"1245–1298","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1287–1339":"1287–1339","1205–1245":"1205–1245","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1298":"1298","1282":"1282","1339":"1339","Stourton, Yorkshire, England":"Stourton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stourton, Wirral, Cheshire, England":"Wirral, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1245–1298":"1245–1298","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1287–1339":"1287–1339","1205–1245":"1205–1245","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1298":"1298","1282":"1282","1339":"1339","Stourton, Yorkshire, England":"Stourton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stourton, Wirral, Cheshire, England":"Wirral, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1245–1298":"1245–1298","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1287–1339":"1287–1339","1205–1245":"1205–1245","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1298":"1298","1282":"1282","1339":"1339","Stourton, Yorkshire, England":"Stourton, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Stourton, Wirral, Cheshire, England":"Wirral, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert de Stourton est né en 1245, à Stourton, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Alexander de Stourton 2 Children. Il a épousé Parnell o